<div id="review_4077211151" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4077211151" />
    <a title="Luís" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/117399210-lu-s"><img alt="Luís" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1636480820p2/117399210.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4077211151?book_show_action=true">Jul 13, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Luís" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Luís" href="/user/show/117399210-lu-s">Luís</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9789722037594" href="/book/show/9477325-oscar-e-lucinda">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=g-historical-fiction">g-historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=g-classics">g-classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=2021-readings">2021-readings</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=g-romance">g-romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=e-4">e-4</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=australia">australia</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4077211151" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5722429184650500966">Oscar and Lucinda is a typically Victorian large-scale novel, a period of the second half of the 19th century marking the height of the industrial revolution, of the British Empire and rich in great stories, which the author successfully contrived to resurrect. The narrator pays his tribute to the original figure of his great-grandfather, Oscar Hopkins.<br/>The latter lives alone in Devon with his father, Theophilus. A member of one of the branches of evangelical Christianity, the Plymouth Brethren. </span>
  <span id="freeText5722429184650500966" style="display:none">Oscar and Lucinda is a typically Victorian large-scale novel, a period of the second half of the 19th century marking the height of the industrial revolution, of the British Empire and rich in great stories, which the author successfully contrived to resurrect. The narrator pays his tribute to the original figure of his great-grandfather, Oscar Hopkins.<br />The latter lives alone in Devon with his father, Theophilus. A member of one of the branches of evangelical Christianity, the Plymouth Brethren. No longer having his mother died of cancer and losing a brother and a sister carried away prematurely by the disease, he is educated in religion's rigorous and rigid principles by his father, a fierce and severe being, and yet magnet. As a result, the child's mind is riddled with a jumble of infantile mysticism, always quick to reject the possibility of coincidences to see everywhere the sign of the presence and the will of God. In any case, he shows excellent consistency in looking for him. By the grace of a somewhat unique hopscotch game, he led to convincing himself that his father is living in error, that he must find the bosom of the Anglican Church, while the latter sees in his prodigal son the instrument of divine wrath in the face of his pride. Oscar leaves his father's house and goes to the Stratton rectory. After studying at Oxford, he became a pastor, a spiritual leader of an unusual type, because he was engaged in the fever of gambling and betting to serve a pious objective: to raise the necessary funds to become a missionary and to evangelise South New Wales from Australia. Oscar is a somewhat grotesque character who would have his place in a Dickensian novel.<br />On the other side of the world, Lucinda Leplastrier, daughter of English settlers living in Australia, leads a life that, at its beginnings, is not unlike that of Oscar. She lost her father thrown down from his mount at an early age, and her mother carried away by the Spanish flu. Inheriting a plump fortune that she has difficulty in assuming, she directs her existence in a free and determined manner, in the throes of attempts to lock her into the world of conventions that society wants her even to adopt. She must arm herself in the face of this human universe. Oscar and Lucinda will meet in the bowels of the liner the Leviathan, brought together by their ludomania, to converge their ordinary madness towards the realisation of an obscure project: the erection of a glass church.<br />The novel, published in 1988, is of a beautiful scale and offers the challenging ambition to be part of the great tradition of the Victorian novel. I particularly appreciated the evocation of the chapel quarrels between Puritan sects of England, the dives in the shallows of London and Sydney, the living tableau of the Leviathan, which was the first giant liner and the largest ship ever. Built-in its time, as well as the narration of the art of glassworking. This work, which is a bit like a novel by training, historical fiction and satire, is a great success, crowned with the 1988 Booker Prize.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5722429184650500966" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


